But how are we to account for these ‘ egregio inspersos corpore naevos ’ἲ Eber- hard suggests that the speech has come down to us exactly as it was taken down by shorthand writers in the senate⁸z and exhibits a few of the inaccuracies ⁴of improvisation. Again, it may have happened that Cicero draughted in the rough a copy of his speech after making it: and that for some reason (possibly the death of Marcellus or his own subsequent attitude towards Caesar) he never gave it a final revision for publication. Others—perhaps Tiro—may have pub- lished it aster his death3 so that here and there the hand of another may be traceable. It is significant that the exact title of the speech is uncertain. But this fact tells against rather than for the ‘ pseud- epigraphic ’ theory. In dealing with a similar question, Prof. Mahaffy has remarked (Gk.
